{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1680"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1680"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.01,0.43,0.02,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108490"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1680"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90877"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45493"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108490"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of worsening bloating, slight abdominal distension and increased frequency of urination. This is accompanied by a disturbing lower abdominal pain for which she regularly applies a heating pad for relief. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol occasionally on weekends. She has never used combined oral contraceptives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 22 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There is net-like hyperpigmentation over the lower abdomen (Image). There is tenderness in the lower abdomen which does not radiate elsewhere, but no mass or ascites is noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis of her presenting symptoms and signs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retroperitoneal haemorrhage","Varicella zoster","Livedo reticularis","Pancreatitis","Ovarian carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skin changes seen in this patient, known as erythema ab igne, are classically seen after persistent and repeated thermal exposure. The underlying diagnosis is most likely \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Ovarian cancer commonly presents in a subacute fashion, with a constellation of symptoms including abdominal or pelvic pain, bloating, early satiety, and urinary urgency and frequency. Some patients attempt to soothe the chronic pain brought by a neoplastic process with repeated application of a heat source, resulting in erythema ab igne. This is an important rash to distinguish as it may mask the serious underlying problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is historically linked to erythema ab igne as patients would often apply heat for pain relief. However, due to progress in pain management, these cutaneous changes are now an uncommon finding. Excessive alcohol consumption is the most common aetiology of chronic pancreatitis, which is not the case in this patient. Patients with chronic pancreatitis commonly experience pain in the epigastrium that radiates to the back, and may present with signs of pancreatic insufficiency such as steatorrhoea and diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELivedo reticularis\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the principal differential diagnoses of erythema ab igne as they have similar clinical morphology. It is often aggravated by cold exposure and is most commonly found on the extremities. It can occur secondary to drug reactions, thrombosis and vasculitis. This would not fit with her other symptoms of bloating and urinary urgency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E can occur spontaneously in patients who are on antiplatelet or anticoagulation therapy, or secondary to trauma, surgery or procedural manipulations. It can also occur as a result of retroperitoneal lesions such as cysts and aneurysms, or spontaneous bleeding from gynaecologic or obstetric conditions. However, these patients usually present with acute abdominal pain, and often have no cutaneous signs. When present, cutaneous signs such as Cullen\u0027s sign (umbilical ecchymosis) and Grey Turner\u0027s sign (flank ecchymosis) are different from the reticulated hyperpigmentation seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella zoster\u003C/strong\u003E virus causes chickenpox, a transmissible disease that is most common in children. It can remain latent in dorsal root ganglia of sensory nerves and reactivate later in life to cause herpes zoster (shingles). Herpes zoster manifests as painful, blistering rashes in a typical belt-like pattern (following the distribution of the affected dermatome) and does not cross the midline. Herpes zoster typically runs a shorter course (usually around two to four weeks), although a small portion of patients can develop postherpetic neuralgia, in which the pain persists even though dermatological manifestations have resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of chronic non-specific abdominal symptoms and erythema ab igne should raise suspicion for an underlying malignancy, particularly ovarian cancer in a woman of this age. The complete history of the patient as well as examination findings is essential rather than only spot diagnosis based on the image.  Further investigations, including pelvic ultrasound and CA-125 levels, would be warranted to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema ab igne is an uncommon dermatological manifestation that occurs after chronic thermal exposure, such as in patients who apply heat to relieve chronic pain.","Ovarian cancer often presents with vague symptoms including abdominal pain, bloating, and urinary frequency.","The combination of erythema ab igne and chronic abdominal symptoms should raise suspicion for underlying malignancy."],"references":["Kozera EK, Sebaratnam DF. Erythema ab igne. Med J Aust. 2021 Nov 1;215(9):405. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34599511/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90877"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1680"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18974"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18974"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f9122aca-562c-4926-ab8d-43efd887b2ef.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f9122aca-562c-4926-ab8d-43efd887b2ef.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"ite